04936nam a22008415i 9780674418813DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20131992mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)900815478  a97806744188137 a10.4159/harvard.97806744188132doi  a(DE-B1597)252762  a(OCoLC)654759987  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aWhite, Dan S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLost Comrades :bSocialists of the Front Generation, 1918-1945 /cDan S. White.  aReprint 2014 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2013] 4c©1992  a1 online resource (255 p.) :b10 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- t1. Who Were the Front Generation? -- t2. Youth and War -- t3. A Season of Learning -- t4. Making Their Way -- t5. Emergence of a Critique -- t6. The Challenge of Fascism -- t7. Visions for the Masses -- t8. Planning -- t9. A Surrender to History -- t10. Paths of Collaboration -- t11. A Struggle with Destiny -- tEpilogue -- tNotes. Note on Sources. Index -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tA Note on Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe concept of generation as a historical category has never been used more effectively than in Lost Comrades. The socialists of the Front Generation, young men in 1914, were driven into political activity and ideological exploration by the experience of the First World War. Their efforts to renew socialism, to carry it beyond Marxism and beyond the working class, were profound and original, yet ultimately they failed. Lost Comrades follows the Front Generation socialists from their questioning of Marxist orthodoxies in the 1920s into their confrontations with the twin challenges of fascism and world depression in the early 1930s. Responding to these dangers, they devised—with little success—counterpropaganda against the fascists and planning blueprints for the economy. Eventually, some of the most prominent—Sir Oswald Mosley in Britain, Hendrik de Man in Belgium, Marcel Déat in France—shifted their hopes to fascism or, dur- ing the Second World War, to collaborationism in Hitler's Europe. Others, however, like Carlo Mierendorff and Theodor Haubach in Germany, ended as martyrs in the anti-Nazi resistance. Yet even these divergent paths showed parallels reflecting their common starting point. In tracing these unfulfilled careers, White brings a new clarity to the hopes and limitations of European socialism between the two world wars.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aGeschichte (1918-1945). 0aSocialism. 0aSocialisme. 0aSocialisten. 0aSocialists. 0aSozialismus. 0aWirtschaft. 4aHISTORY / General. 4aHISTORY / Modern / 20th Century. 4aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Communism, Post-Communism & Socialism. 4aSocialism -- History -- 20th century. 4aSocialists -- Biography. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: World History eBook Packagez9783110353563oZDB-23-HWH08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441879040uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441881340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674418813423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674418813.jpg  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  a